# Pigment design-system standard

One platform team writes these once; every agent edit across 200+ product surfaces inherits
them. The linter can't express "on-brand"; the rule can. Bugbot reviews against it on every PR.

## Tokens & system components, never literals
- Use the Pigment components (`@/components/ui/*`) and the theme tokens
  (`bg-primary`, `text-muted-foreground`, the `Button` `variant` prop, `StatusBadge`). Layer 1
  is **Adobe React Spectrum** behind the stable Pigment API — the default design system (no
  flag), rendered client-only (legacy shadcn/Base UI is the pre-hydration SSR fallback). Product
  teams keep calling the same `<Button variant>` / `<StatusBadge status>` API regardless.
- **Never hardcode a Tailwind color literal** (`bg-pink-500`, `text-[#...]`, raw hex) in a
  product surface under `app/` or `components/campaigns/`. A literal color there bypasses the
  design system — flag it and replace with the right token/variant.
- **Never fight the component.** Don't drop to a raw `<button>`/`<span>` when a system
  component exists, and don't reach for Spectrum `UNSAFE_style` / `UNSAFE_className` to push a
  one-off color onto a Spectrum control. Both abandon the system and won't theme — use the
  component's `variant` / semantic prop instead. (This is the Spectrum-era shape of INJURY A.)
- New semantic values are added to the token source by the platform team (`globals.css`, the
  legacy `STATUS_TOKENS` map in `components/ui/status-tokens.ts`, or a Spectrum semantic
  variant), not inlined by a product team.

## Accessibility is a contract
- Status/text color pairs must meet WCAG AA (4.5:1). `components/ui/status-badge.test.ts`
  enforces it in CI for every status in both light and dark themes.
- Interactive elements keep a visible focus ring.

## Reuse before authoring
- Compose existing `@/components/ui` components before adding new ones. A one-off styled
  element that duplicates a system component is drift.

## Bugbot review posture
- Run LEFT of PR Bugbot and the human merge gate. Prefer a few high-confidence, cross-file
  findings (token drift, a11y regressions, duplicated components) over many shallow nits.
  Cite `file:line` and the rule violated.
